commitResults.messageTitle: Save tasks when list changes and load data on start.
commitResults.messageBody:
Currently, tasks added or updated are not saved when the program is terminated.

Tasks must be saved as users may require the list of tasks the next time they use the program.

Let's save accumulated tasks in a duke.txt file automatically whenever the task list changes and load the task list from the file when the chatbot starts up.

Having a specific file to store the task list allows changes to be saved and loaded easily.

Deadlines are treated as simply strings.

We need to have some form of checking the string input to ensure that a proper date and time is inputted.

Let's verify that the date and time inputted by the user is valid and store it in the Deadline object as a LocalDateTime object.

By doing so, we can be sure that the user has inputted a valid deadline and code is more organised.

commitResults.messageTitle: Manually committing to merge with Level-8 branch
Structure the code using more OOP.
commitResults.messageBody:
Most of the code is cluttered in the Duke.java file.

This makes the card hard to read, and makes it harder to change when the code is not segmented.

Let's edit the code and use more OOP!

Incorporating more OOP makes the code easier to read and more scalable as related fields and methods are grouped together.

commitResults.messageTitle: Encapsulate files in a duke package.
commitResults.messageBody:
All files are currently in the src/main/java directory.

The files must be encapsulated as it is easier to determine which files are related to which.

Let's place all files in a package and include them in that package.

By putting all files under a package, it encapsulates the Duke chatbot and its functionalities.

There is no way of doing automated testing.

Testing our program manually is time consuming and error-prone.

Let's use Gradle to help us automate testing.

Gradle has functions that allow it to test cases automatically.

commitResults.messageTitle: Add one more file that was forgotten in the previous commit.

commitResults.messageBody:
There are no automated test cases to test the code.

We need automated test cases to determine if our code works and to make the testing process more efficient.

Let's implement some JUnit test cases!

By implementing JUnit test cases, we can test our code more easily and efficiently.

The program prints messages which should not be printed, which comes from program testing.

The testing messages must be removed to ensure a seamless experience for users.

Let's remove all testing messages!

By doing so, unnecessary code will not be shown to the users, thus improving their experience.

Classes and methods in the code have no descriptions or explanations.

Users or other programmers may not be able to understand the classes and methods used.

Let's use JavaDocs to document our classes and methods!

JavaDocs provides a structured way of documenting code for others to understand.

Currently, the code does not follow a standard convention.

Code can be hard to read if coding styles are not standardised.

Let's use the SE-EDU Java Coding Standard to standardise the code!

The SE-EDU Java Coding Standard provides a clear and concise coding standard which ensures the code is structured and readable.

There is no way to query the task list using a string.

Users cannot find tasks related to their search keywords.

Let's implement a search feature for users to find tasks related to their query!

Users can now search for tasks related to their query.

commitResults.messageTitle: Add minor improvements in the code

commitResults.messageBody:
The start and end dates inputted into events are not checked whether or not they are actual dates.

This can result in the start and end dates being words instead of dates.

Let's use LocalDateTime for Events as well.

In this way, the start and end dates can be determined efficiently and and effectively.
